'''''Loyalties''''' is a 1999 Canadian documentary film directed by [[Lesley Ann Patten]] about two women—one white, one black—who discover that they are related due to the  legacy of [[slavery in the United States]]. In 1995, Dr. Ruth Whitehead of the [[Nova Scotia Museum of Natural History]] in [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]] met [[Black Canadian]] graduate student Carmelita Robertson, who happened to mention that her relatives came to [[Nova Scotia]] from [[South Carolina]] as [[Black Loyalists]] in the late 18th century. Whitehead, whose own family also came from South Carolina, realized that she recognized some of the names of Robertson's ancestors, and together the two women journey to [[Charleston, South Carolina]] to explore their shared past.<ref>{{cite news|title=Movies & video|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=aJhIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XAoNAAAAIBAJ&pg=3694%2C724763|accessdate=15 July 2012|newspaper=[[The Post and Courier]]|location=Charleston|date=18 March 1999|page=32}}</ref>  The film also exposes strains in the personal relationship between the two women, with Whitehead descended from wealthy slave owners, and Robertson the descendant of their slaves.<ref name=North>{{cite book|title=North of Everything: English-Canadian Cinema Since 1980|publisher=University of Alberta Press|isbn=978-0888643902|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iLNhHWfarosC&pg=PA37&lpg=PA37&dq=Loyalties+NFB+Leslie+patten&source=bl&ots=m4CdGyIn4-&sig=mEWs8Bw07vDYAzoyvC1ngFqHgTQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TpL_T5qZBKrk0QG_o8TqBw&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Loyalties%20NFB%20Leslie%20patten&f=false|editor=William Beard and Gerry White|page=37|chapter=Brave New Film Board|date=1 June 2002}}</ref><ref name=Butcher>{{cite journal|last=Butcher|first=Kristen|title=Loyalties|journal=Canadian Materials|date=8 September 2000|volume=VII|issue=1|url=http://www.umanitoba.ca/cm/vol7/no1/loyalties.html|accessdate=13 July 2012|publisher=Manitoba Library Association|ISSN=1201-9364| format=Review}}</ref>   

''Loyalties'' is co-produced by the [[National Film Board of Canada]] and [[ZIJI Film & Television Productions]].<ref name=nfbcoll>{{cite web|title=Loyalties|work=Collections page|publisher=National Film Board of Canada|url=http://www.onf-nfb.gc.ca/eng/collection/film/?id=33709|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref>

==Awards==
In 1999, ''Loyalties'' received the [[Canada Award]] from the [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television]] and was named Best Social Issue
documentary at [[Hot Docs]]. The following year, it received the [[Golden Sheaf Award]] in the category of Best Multicultural/Race Relations documentary.<ref name=Butcher/><ref name=nfbcoll/>

